1. Problem 1

+1a \[ E[E[X|Y]] = E[X] \] https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Law_of_total_expectation \[E[E[X|Y]] = E_y[\sum_x xP(X=x|Y=y)]\] \[ =\sum_y [\sum_x xP(X=x|Y=y)] P(Y=y) \] \[ =\sum_y \sum_x xP(X=x|Y=y) P(Y=y) \] \[ =\sum_x x \sum_y P(X=x|Y=y) P(Y=y) \] \[ =\sum_x x P(X=x|Y=y) \] \[ =\sum_x xP(X=x) = E[X] \]

+1b \[ Var(X) = E[Var(X|Y)] + Var(E[X|Y]) \] https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Law_of_total_variance
Writing this out in 2 steps makes the math easier to see.
Step 1:
\[ E[Var[X|Y] = E[E[X|Y]^2 + [E[X|Y]]^2] = E[E[X^2|Y]] = E[X^2] \] Step 2: \[ Var[E[X|Y]] = E[[E[X|Y]]^2]-[E[E[X|Y]]]^2 = [E[E[X|Y]]]^2 = [E[X]]^2 \] combining we get:
\[ Var(X) = E[X^2] - E[X]^2 \]
————————————————————————————
+ 2a \[ g(x)=\int{f(x,y)}dy=\int_{-1}^1{(x+y)dy}=xy+\frac{y^2}{2}=x+\frac{1}{2} \] ————————————————————————————
+ 2b \[ w(y|x)=\frac{f(x,y)}{g(x)}=\frac{x+y}{x+\frac{1}{2}} \quad 0\le x\le 1 \\ \] ————————————————————————————
+ 2c Conditional expectation
\[ E[Y|X]=\int_0^1{y p(y|x)dy} \] using: p(y|x) = \(\frac{x+y}{x+1}\)
\[ =\int_0^1 y*\frac{x+y}{x+1\2}dy \]
\[ =\int_0^1{\frac{xy}{x+1/2}}dy+\int_0^1{\frac{y^2}{x+1/2}dy} \] \[ \frac{y^2x}{2(x+1/2)}+\frac{y^3}{3(x+1/2)}\big|_0^1= \frac{x}{2x+1}+\frac{1}{3x+3/2} \] + 2d
\[ \sigma_{X|Y} = E[X|Y] - E[X]E[Y] \] \[ E[X]= \int_0^1\int_0^1 x(x+y)dydx = \int_0^1\int_0^1 x^2+xy dydx= \int_0^1 x^2+\frac{x}{2}dx = \frac{x^3}{3}+\frac{x^2}{2*2}\big|_0^1=\frac{7}{12}\] \[ E[Y] = \int_0^1\int_0^1y(x+y)dydx = \int_0^1\int_0^1y^2+xy dydx=\int_0^1\frac{1}{3}+\frac{x}{2}dx =\frac{x}{3}+\frac{x^2}{2*2}\big|_0^1 = \frac{7}{12} \] \[ E[Y|X] = \int_0^1\int_0^1 xy(x+y)dydx=\int_0^1\int_0^1 x^2y+y^2xdydx = \int_0^1\frac{x^2y^2}{2}+\frac{y^3x}{3}dx = \frac{x^3}{6}+\frac{x^2}{6}\big|_0^1 = \frac{1}{3} \] \[ \sigma_{X|Y} = E[X|Y] - E[X]E[Y]=\frac{1}{3} - \frac{7}{12}\frac{7}{12}=\frac{-1}{144}=-0.0069 \] ——————————————————————————————————————————
# 3. Problem 3
+ 3a We find the density function using the equation: \(f(w(y))*|w'(y)|\)
\[ Y=\sqrt{X} \] \[ X = Y^2 \] \[ w'(y) = \frac{dx}{dy} = 2y \] We get the density function by: \[ p(y) = \lambda e^{-\lambda y^2}|2y| = 2y\lambda e^{-\lambda y^2} \] ——————————————————————————————————————————
+ 3b Cumulative Distribution function: \[ F(y) = P(Y\le y) \] \[ F(y) = \int_0^y \lambda 2ye^{-\lambda y^2}dy \] \[ F(y) = 2\lambda \int_0^y ye^{-\lambda y^2}dy \] \[ = -e^{-\lambda y^2}\big|_0^y \] \[ = -e^{-\lambda y^2}+1 \] Verify F(0) = 0 and \(F(\inf)=1\)
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantile_function
\[ F(0)=-e^{0}+1 = 0 \] and \[ F(\inf) = e^{-\inf}+1 = 0-1 = 1 \] ——————————————————————————————————————————
+ 3c Quantile Function \(F^{-1}\)
\[ 1-e^{-\lambda q^2} = y \] \[ e^{-\lambda q^2} = 1-y \] \[ -\lambda q^2 = ln(1-y) \] \[ q=\sqrt{ \frac{ln(1-y)}{-\lambda}} \] ——————————————————————————————————————————
+ 3d find E[Y], Var(Y) \[ E[Y] = \int y *f(y) dy = \int 2y^2 \lambda e^{-\lambda*y^2}dy \] \[ u = y \] \[ dv = 2\lambda y e^{-\lambda y^2}dy \] \[ du = dy \] \[ v = -e^{-\lambda y^2} \] To intgrate \(e^{-x^2}\) used the solution from: http://math.stackexchange.com/questions/154968/is-there-really-no-way-to-integrate-e-x2 \[ \int e^{-x^2} = \sqrt{\pi} \] or with a constant we can say: \[ \int e^{-\lambda x^2} = \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{\lambda}} \] https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaussian_integral \[ uv - \int vdu = ye^{-\lambda y^2} - \int -e^{-\lambda y^2}dy \] \[ E[Y] = ye^{-\lambda y^2} + \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{\lambda}} \] ———————————————————————————————– \[ E[Y^2] = \int y^2 *f(x)dx = \int 2y^3\lambda e^{-\lambda*y^2}dy \] \[ u = y^2 \] \[ dv = 2\lambda y e^{-\lambda y^2}dy \] \[ du = 2ydy \] \[ v = -e^{-\lambda y^2} \] \[ uv - \int vdu = -y^2e^{-\lambda y^2} - \int -2ye^{-\lambda y^2}dy \] \[ \int 2ye^{-\lambda y^2}dy = \frac{-1}{\lambda} e^{-\lambda y^2} \] \[ E[Y^2] = -y^2e^{-\lambda y^2}+ \frac{-1}{\lambda} e^{-\lambda y^2}\] Variance can now be solved for: \[var(Y) = E[Y^2]-E[Y]^2 \] \[ = -y^2e^{-\lambda y^2}+ \frac{-1}{\lambda} e^{-\lambda y^2} - (ye^{-\lambda y^2} + \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{\lambda}})^2 \] ———————————————————————————————————————————–
# 4. Problem 4 Find the MLE for Y from the pdf above \[ p(y)=\lambda 2ye^{-\lambda y^2} \] \[ L(\lambda)=\prod_1^n{\lambda 2y_ie^{-\lambda y_i^2}} \] We take the log of both sides then differentiate to find the MLE for \(\lambda\). \[ \frac{d(ln(L(X)))}{d\lambda}= \frac{d(n ln(2\lambda))}{d\lambda}+\frac{d(ln\prod(y_ie^{-y_i^2\lambda})}{d\lambda} = 0 \] Split the terms and differentiate to make the math easier. \[ \frac{d(n ln(2\lambda))}{d\lambda}= \frac{n}{\lambda} \] \[ \frac{d(ln \prod{y_i e^{-y_i^2\lambda}})}{d\lambda} = \frac{d(ln(\prod{y_i}) + ln(\prod{e^{-\lambda y_i^2}})))}{d\lambda} = \frac{d(\sum{ln(y_i)} + \sum{ln e^{-\lambda y_i^2}})}{d\lambda} = 0 - \sum{y_i^2} \] combine our results to get: \[ 0 = \frac{n}{\lambda} - \sum y_i^2 \] solve for lambda: \[ \frac{n}{\lambda} -\sum{y_i^2} = 0 \] \[ \lambda = \frac{n}{\sum{y_i^2}} \]

# This function takes a number a lambda value for the Y = sqrt(X) exponential distribution
exp_function <- function(n,lam)
{
  x <- c(runif(n))
  Y <-sqrt(log(1-x)/-lam)
  return (Y)
}
Y = exp_function(10000,2)
hist(Y, freq=FALSE)
lines(Y,2*2*Y*exp(-2*Y^2), col="red")
